        "body": "Thanks for the issue @epizut.\r\n\r\nIf I understand correctly, you're asking for different behavior than we currently get with the `freq` kwarg.\r\n\r\nLet's say we have a time series that starts at 11:35 pm. \r\n\r\n```python\r\nts = (\r\n    dd.demo.make_timeseries()\r\n      .loc[\"2000-02-15 23:35:30\":, :]\r\n      .repartition(freq='1D')\r\n)\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf we use `freq` to repartition by `1D`, our first and second partitions start/stop as follows:\r\n\r\nPartition | Start  | Stop |\r\n| ------- | ------------- | ------------- |\r\n| 0 | 2000-02-15 23:35:30 | 2000-02-15 23:59:50  |\r\n| 1 | 2000-02-16 00:00:00 | 2000-02-16 23:59:50  |\r\n\r\n\r\nWhereas in your proposed scenario, we could to:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nts = (\r\n    dd.demo.make_timeseries()\r\n      .loc[\"2000-02-15 23:35:30\":, :]\r\n      .repartition(divisions='1D')\r\n)\r\n```\r\n\r\nto get:\r\n\r\nPartition | Start  | Stop |\r\n| ------- | ------------- | ------------- |\r\n| 0 | 2000-02-15 23:35:30 | 2000-02-16 23:35:20  |\r\n| 1 | 2000-02-16 23:35:30 | 2000-02-17  23:35:20  |\r\n\r\n\r\nDo I have that right?",
